{"version":3,"kind":"Article","sha256":"2e9055bc9bee93617b08c6b9601fe279c03db55ef046cdb74d997179bcfa2087","slug":"chapter-02","location":"/mdbook/src/chapter_02.md","dependencies":[],"frontmatter":{"title":"Acquiring and Running Rattlesnake","numbering":{"heading_1":{"enabled":true,"continue":false},"heading_2":{"start":2,"enabled":true,"template":"Chapter %s"},"figure":{"enumerator":"2.%s","enabled":true,"continue":false},"table":{"enumerator":"2.%s","enabled":true,"continue":false},"equation":{"enumerator":"2.%s","enabled":true,"continue":false},"heading_3":{"enabled":true},"heading_4":{"enabled":true},"heading_5":{"enabled":true},"heading_6":{"enabled":true},"code":{"enumerator":"2.%s","enabled":true},"title":{"offset":1}},"content_includes_title":false,"github":"https://github.com/sandialabs/rattlesnake-vibration-controller","keywords":["mimo","vibration","modal","structural-dynamics"],"abbreviations":{"6DoF":"Six Degree-of-Freedom","API":"Application Programming Interface","APSD":"Auto-Power Spectral Density","CCLD":"Constant Current Line Drive","COLA":"Constant Overlap and Add","CPSD":"Cross-Power Spectral Density","FEM":"Finite Element Model","FFT":"Fast Fourier Transform","FRF":"Frequency Response Function","GUI":"Graphical User Interface","ICP":"Integrated Circuit Piezoelectric","IDE":"Integrated Development Environment","IEPE":"Integrated Electronics PiezoElectric","IFFT":"Inverse Fast Fourier Transform","IP":"Internet Protocol","JSON":"Javascript Object Notation","MIMO":"Multiple Input, Multiple Output","ReST":"Representational State Transfer","RMS":"Root-Mean-Square","SVD":"Singular Value Decomposition","TRAC":"Time Response Assurance Criterion","UI":"User Interface"},"source_url":"https://github.com/sandialabs/rattlesnake-vibration-controller/blob/main/documentation/mdbook/src/chapter_02.md","edit_url":"https://github.com/sandialabs/rattlesnake-vibration-controller/edit/main/documentation/mdbook/src/chapter_02.md","thumbnail":"/build/spyder_run_configura-dbd6f7aea6160803d0cd534be485b5db.png","exports":[{"format":"md","filename":"chapter_02.md","url":"/build/chapter_02-fd2c11728a7f9d53833c1839a614a7f3.md"}]},"mdast":{"type":"root","children":[{"type":"block","children":[{"type":"heading","depth":2,"position":{"start":{"line":17,"column":1},"end":{"line":17,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Acquiring and Running Rattlesnake","position":{"start":{"line":17,"column":1},"end":{"line":17,"column":1}},"key":"MA2Rnj5J8L"}],"label":"sec:acquiring_and_running_rattlesnake","identifier":"sec:acquiring_and_running_rattlesnake","html_id":"sec-acquiring-and-running-rattlesnake","enumerator":"2","key":"ZaRQhtah8G"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":19,"column":1},"end":{"line":19,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Two methods are provided to acquire the Rattlesnake software.  The software can be downloaded as an executable and run directly with no other dependencies.  Alternatively, the software can be downloaded in its Python script form and run using a Python interpreter.  The former approach is simpler, but results in a larger file size and longer software loading time due to the necessity to pack the Python ecosystem into the executable for distribution and unpack it prior to execution.  The latter approach is more suited to users who wish to utilize the full functionality of the Rattlesnake framework, which would include activities such as coding up custom control laws.  In this case, it will be advantageous to have a Python ecosystem installed on the user’s computer, so simply downloading the source code and executing it similarly to other Python scripts will potentially be easier than the executable approach.","position":{"start":{"line":19,"column":1},"end":{"line":19,"column":1}},"key":"FKzStoO19Q"}],"key":"gUlG6xV2a1"},{"type":"heading","depth":3,"position":{"start":{"line":21,"column":1},"end":{"line":21,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Running from an Executable","position":{"start":{"line":21,"column":1},"end":{"line":21,"column":1}},"key":"v0Nc3c8uZh"}],"identifier":"running-from-an-executable","label":"Running from an Executable","html_id":"running-from-an-executable","implicit":true,"enumerator":"2.1","key":"MpoUGDrUNk"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":23,"column":1},"end":{"line":23,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Python code can be compiled into a single executable file, which makes it easier to distribute Python code.  The user need not have a Python distribution installed on their computer to simply run the executable, as the executable will contain the required Python interpreter and libraries compiled within it.  The executable approach has a few disadvantages.  The file size of the executable will generally be larger than the raw source code.  Additionally, the executable will generally be slower to start due to the necessary unpacking of the Python ecosystem from it.  Still, if a user is not familiar with Python, the executable will be the easiest approach to run the software.","position":{"start":{"line":23,"column":1},"end":{"line":23,"column":1}},"key":"TJB7r0sGDf"}],"key":"LLvab0y7wX"},{"type":"heading","depth":4,"position":{"start":{"line":25,"column":1},"end":{"line":25,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Downloading the Executable","position":{"start":{"line":25,"column":1},"end":{"line":25,"column":1}},"key":"YXLCOjNDRH"}],"identifier":"downloading-the-executable","label":"Downloading the Executable","html_id":"downloading-the-executable","implicit":true,"enumerator":"2.1.1","key":"syaGRPu0Wo"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":27,"column":1},"end":{"line":27,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Executables for Rattlesnake are generally stored in the ","position":{"start":{"line":27,"column":1},"end":{"line":27,"column":1}},"key":"cSnd8iR7uC"},{"type":"link","url":"https://github.com/sandialabs/rattlesnake-vibration-controller","position":{"start":{"line":27,"column":1},"end":{"line":27,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"GitHub Project","position":{"start":{"line":27,"column":1},"end":{"line":27,"column":1}},"key":"XxNeUPBfKM"}],"urlSource":"https://github.com/sandialabs/rattlesnake-vibration-controller","error":true,"key":"NEZ6fY9IeY"},{"type":"text","value":" on the ","position":{"start":{"line":27,"column":1},"end":{"line":27,"column":1}},"key":"Qw9kFuMWQZ"},{"type":"link","url":"https://github.com/sandialabs/rattlesnake-vibration-controller/releases","position":{"start":{"line":27,"column":1},"end":{"line":27,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"GitHub Releases page","position":{"start":{"line":27,"column":1},"end":{"line":27,"column":1}},"key":"AyhSq4HkpK"}],"urlSource":"https://github.com/sandialabs/rattlesnake-vibration-controller/releases","error":true,"key":"OIZihl5cWg"},{"type":"text","value":".  A user can simply download the executable corresponding to the user’s operating system and save it to their computer.  No installation is necessary to run this executable.","position":{"start":{"line":27,"column":1},"end":{"line":27,"column":1}},"key":"JJkBvmI9GK"}],"key":"HFJuVbnKX3"},{"type":"heading","depth":4,"position":{"start":{"line":29,"column":1},"end":{"line":29,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Running the Executable","position":{"start":{"line":29,"column":1},"end":{"line":29,"column":1}},"key":"oOhATxfP3L"}],"identifier":"running-the-executable","label":"Running the Executable","html_id":"running-the-executable","implicit":true,"enumerator":"2.1.2","key":"R7FK5jhh7u"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":31,"column":1},"end":{"line":31,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Running Rattlesnake from an executable is as simple as running any other program.  Simply double click on the executable (or otherwise execute it) and the program will run.  Note that there may be a significant delay between executing the executable and the program appearing, as the executable will unpack a Python distribution into the user’s temporary space in order to run the included Python code.","position":{"start":{"line":31,"column":1},"end":{"line":31,"column":1}},"key":"iu1aV4RCi8"}],"key":"NomZJMVsn5"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":33,"column":1},"end":{"line":33,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"As with any other executable program, users may create links to the program to put on the desktop or in the start menu to make accessing the program easier.","position":{"start":{"line":33,"column":1},"end":{"line":33,"column":1}},"key":"GhPM5xOYNX"}],"key":"hF8nvv6ZQV"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":35,"column":1},"end":{"line":35,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"It may be beneficial to run the executable through the command terminal, as otherwise if an error occurs in the program, the program may simply disappear without the user being aware of any errors.  When running through the command terminal, the user will be able to view any error messages if the program unexpectedly exits, which will be useful in diagnosing the issue if submitted to the issue tracker in the ","position":{"start":{"line":35,"column":1},"end":{"line":35,"column":1}},"key":"yQiauIpZzh"},{"type":"link","url":"https://github.com/sandialabs/rattlesnake-vibration-controller/issues","position":{"start":{"line":35,"column":1},"end":{"line":35,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"GitHub Issues","position":{"start":{"line":35,"column":1},"end":{"line":35,"column":1}},"key":"fN2LAedEa0"}],"urlSource":"https://github.com/sandialabs/rattlesnake-vibration-controller/issues","error":true,"key":"zAnsXOf8DI"},{"type":"text","value":" (See ","position":{"start":{"line":35,"column":1},"end":{"line":35,"column":1}},"key":"FxjhhLd3GL"},{"type":"crossReference","identifier":"sec:obtaining_support","label":"sec:obtaining_support","kind":"heading","position":{"start":{"line"